      "content": "Getting service boundaries right before writing code is the single determinant of migration success. Wrong boundaries create distributed monoliths with network latency, synchronous coupling, and unrecoverable architectural debt. The failure mode: teams decompose along organizational lines or technical layers rather than business capabilities, resulting in services that cannot fulfill their core responsibility independently (e.g., OrderService requiring 6 synchronous calls, PaymentService calling back into monolith). Six months in, features take longer than monolith. Migration fails. Recovery requires complete re-architecture. **Test for right boundaries:** Each service must be able to fulfill its core responsibility if every other service is down. Any service that requires synchronous calls to others to complete its primary function has a wrong boundary. **Dependency matrix as validation tool:** Build a grid before coding; mark every \"this service needs to call that service\" relationship. Any cycle in the matrix indicates a wrong boundary \u2014 reorganize before proceeding. **For this specific migration:** Payment service is the forcing function. However, the boundary design must now account for **consistency requirements**: if payments and inventory must maintain transactional consistency (shared ACID boundary), they should be extracted together and kept in a single service until saga infrastructure is proven. This is a special case of the independence rule \u2014 not independence from each other, but independence from the rest of the system. After saga patterns are proven on lower-risk workflows, payments can split from inventory. Auth should have zero dependencies itself; token validation works standalone. Inventory owns stock levels exclusively; fulfillment reserves inventory but inventory does not call fulfillment back. Fulfillment orchestrates through events, not direct calls. No service should tolerate direct coupling back to monolith for